    <name>AOI03 Internal OSM Candidate VLM Review Queue</name>

    <Placemark>
      <name>1. osm_way_295041873</name>
      <description><![CDATA[<b>Warning:</b> INTERNAL REVIEW ONLY. OpenStreetMap footprint candidate, not official EMS damage. VLM before/after output is a triage aid only; absence/presence here is not confirmation.<br/><b>VLM:</b> likely_destroyed confidence 0.75<br/><b>Evidence:</b> In the before image, a multi-story building with a reddish-brown roof is clearly visible within the candidate footprint. In the after image, the structure is absent and replaced by a debris-toned patch consistent with rubble/collapse. The footprint shape is no longer discernible as a building; only an irregular ground texture remains within the outlined area.<br/><b>Uncertainty:</b> Lower resolution and pixelation of the post-event chip make it difficult to confirm whether the structure fully collapsed versus being reduced to a low rubble pile. Some adjacent tree cover in the before image could partially mask a still-standing low remnant, and the resolution gap limits confidence from ~0.85 to 0.75.<br/><b>Google Maps:</b> <a href='https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&amp;query=10.47229245,-66.95783665'>open</a>]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>-66.95783665,10.47229245,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>2. osm_way_287205261</name>
      <description><![CDATA[<b>Warning:</b> INTERNAL REVIEW ONLY. OpenStreetMap footprint candidate, not official EMS damage. VLM before/after output is a triage aid only; absence/presence here is not confirmation.<br/><b>VLM:</b> possible_major_damage confidence 0.62<br/><b>Evidence:</b> Distinctive reddish/orange roof surface and clear building height/edge signature visible in the before image are absent in the after image. The footprint area in the after image shows a lighter, more uniform patch consistent with debris/rubble rather than an intact roofed structure. Loss of shadow/height signature where a multi-story building previously cast a clear shadow.<br/><b>Uncertainty:</b> After image quality is materially lower (hazier, lower resolution, more washed out) than the before scene, which makes it difficult to distinguish between total destruction, severe collapse, or heavy debris coverage. The clear loss of roof/height is strong evidence of major damage, but the reduced fidelity prevents a high-confidence likely_destroyed call.<br/><b>Google Maps:</b> <a href='https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&amp;query=10.430735975,-66.963376625'>open</a>]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>-66.963376625,10.430735975,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>3. osm_way_226086257</name>
      <description><![CDATA[<b>Warning:</b> INTERNAL REVIEW ONLY. OpenStreetMap footprint candidate, not official EMS damage. VLM before/after output is a triage aid only; absence/presence here is not confirmation.<br/><b>VLM:</b> possible_major_damage confidence 0.55<br/><b>Evidence:</b> Within the yellow/black candidate footprint, the pre-event scene shows a clearly defined multi-story building with visible rooftop structure (mechanical/roof features) and cast shadows indicating substantial height. In the post-event scene, the same footprint contains bright white/light-toned material with irregular texture consistent with debris or exposed rubble; the original roofline and rooftop features are no longer discernible, and the height/shadow signature has been lost.<br/><b>Uncertainty:</b> Resolution and haze in the post-event image limit certainty about whether the white material represents total collapse versus partial damage with debris accumulation or a temporary covering. Higher-resolution follow-up imagery is needed to confirm destruction grade.<br/><b>Google Maps:</b> <a href='https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&amp;query=10.434729175,-66.96909175'>open</a>]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>-66.96909175,10.434729175,0</coordinates></Point>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>4. osm_way_295041872</name>
      <description><![CDATA[<b>Warning:</b> INTERNAL REVIEW ONLY. OpenStreetMap footprint candidate, not official EMS damage. VLM before/after output is a triage aid only; absence/presence here is not confirmation.<br/><b>VLM:</b> possible_major_damage confidence 0.55<br/><b>Evidence:</b> Distinct roof structure with visible rooftop features in the before image is absent in the after image. Within the footprint outline, the after image shows a darker, irregular patch with light-toned material consistent with debris/rubble rather than an intact roof plane. The footprint shape is no longer traceable as a clean rectilinear building form.<br/><b>Uncertainty:</b> While the loss of the roof structure and presence of debris-like texture strongly suggest major damage, the very low resolution and pixelation of the post-event EMS chip prevent definitive confirmation of collapse versus partial debris on a still-standing base. Better-resolution follow-up imagery is needed to upgrade to likely_destroyed.<br/><b>Google Maps:</b> <a href='https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1&amp;query=10.47184365,-66.957774'>open</a>]]></description>
      <Point><coordinates>-66.957774,10.47184365,0</coordinates></Point>
